Danielson Regression

Code 
library(tidyverse)
library(arrow)
library(ResourceSelection)
library(ggpubr)
library(pander)

all <- read_parquet("../../Scripts/All_teacher_info.parquet") %>%
  filter(!is.na(Danielson_492) & gradType %in% c('Grad:Teacher')) %>%
  filter(FirstSemAge<31) %>%
  mutate(minorGroups = case_when(
    lastMinor %in% c('Earth Science Education','Physical Science Ed','Physics Education','Mathematics Education','Biology Education','Chemistry Education','Natural Science Educ','Health Education')~'STEM Minor',
    lastMinor %in% c('American Gov Education','Geography Education','Art Education','Theatre Education','Middle School General Sc')~'SocSci Minor',
    lastMinor %in% c('French Education','Spanish Education','Teach Eng Second Lang')~'Lang Minor',
    lastMinor %in% c('English Education')~'English Minor'),
  Gender = ifelse(isMale==0,'Female','Male')
)
Code 
numerics <- all %>% select(where(is.numeric) & !contains('Danielson'))
col_means <- colMeans(numerics, na.rm = TRUE)
for (col in seq_along(numerics)) {
  numerics[[col]][is.na(numerics[[col]])] <- col_means[col]
}

colnames(numerics) <- paste0(colnames(numerics), "_no_na")

data <- cbind(numerics,all)

Danielson

This analysis builds off the aggregation of Danielson observations recorded in this article.
In summary, weâve condensed down the Danielson observations across dozens of classes and individual reports based on three criteria:

  1. For this analysis, weâve kept only the students with Danielson observations for their ED 492 class, to maximize comparability across students.
  2. If a student has more than one observation recorded for the class, we prioritize the summative evaluations over the formative ones.
  3. To compensate for different grading standards across teachers, weâve turned each raw final score (a 3-pt scale of 22 questions) into a z_score. Now each score reflects how the student did in this class compared to their peers.-

\[ zscore = \frac{x_{StudentScore} - \mu_{TeacherAndSemester}}{\sigma_{TeacherAndSemester}} \]

After these steps, we go from 9854 individual observations to 779 unique student records.

Code 
all %>%
  select(Danielson_492,FinalCumGPA,ACTSAT_Scores,isMale,
         ReceivedPell,BinaryEthnicity, NumSem, YearStarted) %>%
  head(5) %>%
  pander()

Danielson against Disposition

These two features have a strong positive relationship. Many of these students were tested by the same teacher for both types of evaluation, so the correlation may be influenced by the same source.

We have a number of different ways to measure Disposition scores, because theyâre given in a variety of classes on a variety of metrics.

  • The 200-, 300- or 400-level courses independently, for tracking progression through the their teaching development.
  • The last class they took.
  • A score re-weighted based on the z-score of the teacherâs students.

```{r, warning=FALSE}
library(arrow)
library(ResourceSelection)

all <- read_parquet("../../Scripts/All_teacher_info.parquet") %>%
  filter(!is.na(Danielson_492) & gradType %in% c('Grad:Teacher')) %>%
  filter(FirstSemAge<31) %>%
  mutate(minorGroups = case_when(
    lastMinor %in% c('Earth Science Education','Physical Science Ed','Physics Education','Mathematics Education','Biology Education','Chemistry Education','Natural Science Educ','Health Education')~'STEM Minor',
    lastMinor %in% c('American Gov Education','Geography Education','Art Education','Theatre Education','Middle School General Sc')~'SocSci Minor',
    lastMinor %in% c('French Education','Spanish Education','Teach Eng Second Lang')~'Lang Minor',
    lastMinor %in% c('English Education')~'English Minor'),
  Gender = ifelse(isMale==0,'Female','Male')
)

```

```{r}
numerics <- all %>% select(where(is.numeric) & !contains('Danielson'))
col_means <- colMeans(numerics, na.rm = TRUE)
for (col in seq_along(numerics)) {

}

data <- cbind(numerics,all)
```

## Danielson

This analysis builds off the aggregation of Danielson observations recorded in [this article](https://sites.google.com/view/benjamin-pacini/dissertation/data-overview/danielson-fft?authuser=0).<br> In summary, we've condensed down the Danielson observations across dozens of classes and individual reports based on three criteria:

1.  For this analysis, we've kept *only* the students with Danielson observations for their ED 492 class, to maximize comparability across students.
2.  If a student has more than one observation recorded for the class, we prioritize the summative evaluations over the formative ones.
3.  To compensate for different grading standards across teachers, we've turned each raw final score (a 3-pt scale of 22 questions) into a z_score. Now each score reflects how the student did in this class compared to their peers.-

$$
zscore = \frac{x_{StudentScore} - \mu_{TeacherAndSemester}}{\sigma_{TeacherAndSemester}}
$$ 

After these steps, we go from 9854 individual observations to 779 unique student records.

```{r}
all %>%
  select(Danielson_492,FinalCumGPA,ACTSAT_Scores,isMale,
         ReceivedPell,BinaryEthnicity, NumSem, YearStarted) %>%
  head(5) %>%
  pander()
```

It's important to notice that because we made all these adjustments from the raw observations, this analysis won't be useful for predicting individual scores. This can only tell which other metrics are most likely to help students succeed.

```{r}
lm_dan_gpa <- lm(Danielson_492 ~ FinalCumGPA, data = all)
summary(lm_dan_gpa) %>% pander::pander()
```

```{r}
    title="Effect of Final GPA")
```

## Danielson against Disposition

These two features have a strong positive relationship. Many of these students were tested by the same teacher for both types of evaluation, so the correlation may be influenced by the same source.

We have a number of different ways to measure Disposition scores, because they're given in a variety of classes on a variety of metrics.

+ The 200-, 300- or 400-level courses independently, for tracking progression through the their teaching development.
+ The last class they took.
+ A score re-weighted based on the z-score of the teacher's students.

```{r}
lm_dan_disp <- lm(Danielson_492 ~  Disposition_avg+Disposition_highest_level+  Disposition_300+Disposition_400+ Disposition_200+Disposition_highest_level, data = all)
summary(lm_dan_disp) %>% pander::pander()
```

Of all the different variations, the measure built on the last class the student takes is the most effective.
